hands_on_practices.problem:
In spectrometric identification of aromatic compounds, out-of-plane carbon–hydrogen bending vibrations in benzene derivatives serve as diagnostic markers for substitution patterns because they are sensitive to the local mass distribution while largely preserving the same local restoring force when isotopically substituted. Consider a para-disubstituted benzene whose out-of-plane carbon–hydrogen bend is observed at a wavenumber of $	ilde{
u}_{\mathrm{CH}} = 825\ \mathrm{cm}^{-1}$ in Infrared (IR) spectroscopy. Assume the bending coordinate can be modeled as a small-amplitude harmonic motion of the hydrogen (or its isotopologue deuterium) relative to a rigid aromatic ring treated as an effective mass. The potential near equilibrium is quadratic with a force constant $k$ that is unchanged by isotopic substitution, and the kinetic term is governed by the reduced mass of a two-body system composed of the atom $X \in \{\mathrm{H}, \mathrm{D}\}$ and the ring.

Use the fundamental definition of reduced mass for a two-body system and the harmonic oscillator model to derive the dependence of the vibrational wavenumber on the reduced mass, then estimate the expected isotopic shift upon deuteration. Take the effective mass of the ring to be $M_{\mathrm{eff}} = 72.00\ \mathrm{u}$, the hydrogen mass $m_{\mathrm{H}} = 1.007825\ \mathrm{u}$, and the deuterium mass $m_{\mathrm{D}} = 2.014102\ \mathrm{u}$, where $\mathrm{u}$ denotes the atomic mass unit. Compute the deuterated wavenumber $	ilde{
u}_{\mathrm{CD}}$ and the downward shift $\Delta 	ilde{
u} = 	ilde{
u}_{\mathrm{CH}} - 	ilde{
u}_{\mathrm{CD}}$. Round your final shift to four significant figures. Express the final answer in $\mathrm{cm}^{-1}$.
